comments: Also known as "New Roman" or "Unified Script". Herb Purnell says there are two slightly different versions of this orthography being used in China vs. elsewhere. These mostly involve how to handle tone sandhi compounds, presyllables, palatal consonants, and occasional dialect differences. On the one hand, the number of affected words is somewhat large (e.g. every word with a palatal initial). On the other hand, it seems that the attitude of Iu Mien writers is quite tolerant and accepting of variation, so two separate tags may be unnecessary and even problematic. - SVW
